Response to
Episode 3 - "When Knowledge Conquered Fear"
@-------------------------------------------------
-Human pattern regonition a double edged sword: yes, it is a gift that has advanced our race and science, but we oftentimes see patterns that arent really there.
-We know names of serial killers, but not Jan Oort. How much does society really value science?
-prisoners of earth, limits our knowledge
-In 18th century England, coffeehouses were the centers of political/scientific thought, "labratory of democracy", if you will. Funny how coffee still plays a vital role in the lives of programmers and scientists today.  
-The importnace of curiosity cannot be understated. We are all born curious, according to Tyson, but lose our native curiousity when in school, when people teach us things instead of us figuring them out ourselves. How are kids expected to solve problems if in school they are SHOWN solutions, not FINDING them. Perhaps that's what Mr. Brown is doing with this course and the QAF.
-Tyson makes a good point; in a sense we are still babies in the context of astronomy. Not just astronomy, all fields of science and everything. Is knowledge boundless? Is there a limit for perfection? Deep questions we must consider as we further progress into the technologically advanced 21st century. 
